  "market_context": "EUR/USD is in a bearish daily trend. Price rallies up to sweep the previous day's high and closes back inside the prior day's range, forming a daily candle 2 closure that supports continuation lower.",
  "key_observation": "The first hourly sweep of the previous day high failed to confirm a protected high because no closure through the series of down-close candles occurred. A second sweep produced the required closure, validating the protected high and bearish continuation.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the daily chart, identify bearish bias and observe price sweeping the previous day high and closing back inside the prior day's range (candle 2 closure).",
    "Step 2: Drop to the hourly chart to find a protected high; the initial sweep of the previous day high (turtle soup) fails because no closure through the series of down-close candles forming that high occurred.",
    "Step 3: Wait for a second sweep of the high; this time price closes through the candle(s) that made the high, confirming a protected high and a bearish trend flip on the hourly.",
    "Step 4: Anticipate the wick to remain intact and use subsequent up-close-candle closures as continuation entries — each new high sweep followed by a closure through up-close candles forms a new protected high.",
    "Step 5: Target marked liquidity points (previous lows) below; observe deep retracements into fair value gaps that hold the protected high before continuation lower.",
    "Step 6: Confirm the trend remains intact as daily candles close outside the previous day's lows, with target lows eventually being taken."
  ],
  "outcome": "Bearish continuation played out — the protected high held, price reached the targeted lows, and daily candles closed outside previous day lows confirming the trend.",
  "lessons": "A swing high is only protected once price closes through the series of up-close candles that formed it. Without that closure, a sweep is just a failed reversal attempt. Wait for the change in state of delivery before trusting the high.",
